{"number":"0001","startingCode":"void setup() {\n  // put your setup code here, to run once:\n  Serial.begin(9600);\n\n  Serial.println(\"Declare pin in setup and initialize to:\");\n  int pin = 8;\n  Serial.println(pin);\n  \n  Serial.println(\"Use a while loop and decrementing to set the pinModes.\");\n  while(pin >= 2) {\n    pinMode(pin, OUTPUT);  \n    pin--;   \n  }\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  // put your main code here, to run repeatedly:\n  Serial.println(\"Declare pin in loop and initialize to:\");\n  //TODO: Add missing line here\n  Serial.println(pin);\n  digitalWrite(pin, HIGH);\n  delay(pin * 100);\n  \n  Serial.println(\"Compound multiplication: pin *= n; pin is:\");\n  pin *= 2;\n  Serial.println(pin);\n  digitalWrite(pin, HIGH);\n  delay(pin * 100);\n\n  //TODO: Add missing lines here\n\n}","suffix":"int main() {\nsetup();\nloop();\nreturn 0;\n}\n","board":{"type":"LED Board","setup":{"pinKeyframes":[]}},"frameManager":null,"directions":"Exercise0001: Turn on an LED.\n \nNEW:  digitalWrite(2,HIGH); \nDESCRIPTION: Tells Arduino to send enough power to make LED attached to pin 2 light up.\n\n ACTIVITIES:\n1.\tCopy the program from Starting Point Exercise02 into the Arduino IDE. Compile and upload this program to the Arduino and verify that LED 2 lights up.\n2.\tExercise: Remove the; from the end of the line: digitalWrite(2, HIGH);\n3.\t Try to compile and upload the program. You should get a compiler error.\n4.\tLook at the compiler error (red cryptic message at bottom of screen) – this it what happens when we are missing a semi-colon\n5.\tFix the program so it compiles (put the ; back in at the end of digitalWrite(2, HIGH);\n6.\tVerify that there is no compiler error and that LED 2 lights up.\n7.\tModify the program so the Arduino Turns on LEDs 2 and 3.\n8.\tModify the program so the Arduino Turns on LEDs 2, 3 and 4.\n9.\tSave the completed sketch as YourFirstLastName_Exercise02 in: Documents – Arduino – Exercises\n10.\tCreate a file that contains your ani